We present a systematic analysis of the Learned Iterative Shrinkage-Thresholding Algorithm (LISTA) for sparse channel estimation, revealing a fundamental disconnect between estimation accuracy and equalization performance. Our central finding is a mechanism analysis demonstrating that LISTA concentrates $100.0\% \pm 0.0\%$ of estimation error on true tap locations (vs.~$95.2\% \pm 0.6\%$ for OMP and $92.4\% \pm 0.4\%$ for ISTA; mean $\pm$ std over 20 seeds), placing $267\times$ less error on non-support taps. Pre-thresholding analysis ($68.3\%$ before thresholding) and an ISTA control experiment ($92.4\%$) confirm this is a learned property enhanced by $\mathbf{W}^{(k)}$, not a trivial artifact. The mechanism transfers to $K=10$ ($99.9\% \pm 0.1\%$), ITU channels ($99.3$--$99.5\%$), and complex-valued channels ($97.8\%$). Despite LISTA's NMSE saturation at $-25$~dB on i.i.d.~Gaussian channels (trailing OMP by 13--33~dB), this error concentration provides tangible BER benefits under ZF equalization for 16-QAM at SNR $\geq 15$~dB (Holm--Bonferroni corrected $p < 0.05$). Under MMSE equalization, all estimators converge to similar BER at SNR $\geq 5$~dB. Ablation with 20 seeds reveals the per-layer threshold schedule is dominant ($+14$--$18$~dB) and $\mathbf{W}^{(k)}$ contributes $+1.24$~dB ($p < 0.001$). SNR-specific training mitigates the saturation, achieving $-31$~dB ($6$~dB improvement). We contextualize the error concentration within approximate message passing (AMP) theory, connecting LISTA's learned weight matrices to the Onsager correction mechanism.
